         <abstract>
            <p>
               <foreign xml:lang="gez">Saʿātāt za-gǝbṣ</foreign> is a version of the
               <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1961Mashaf">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</ref>, a Church service made up of psalms, biblical readings and hymns.
               It is taken from the Copto-Arabic tradition, but contains significant additional material. The date of the translation into Gǝʿǝz is unknown, according to the teachers of the <foreign xml:lang="gez">Qǝddāse bet</foreign>, it was spread
               in the <date>13th century</date> by <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9162TaklaHa">Takla Hāymānot</persName> and his monastic network. </p>
           <p>The three other types of Maṣḥafa saʿātāt identified by  <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/DZFI5RB2"><seg type="book"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/><title level="m">The liturgy of the hours in East and West: the origins of the Divine Office and its meaning for today</title><author><forename>Robert F.</forename><surname>Taft</surname></author><pubPlace>Collegeville, Minn.</pubPlace><publisher>The Liturgical Pr.</publisher><date>1986</date><note type="tags"><note type="tag">bm:Taft1986Liturgy</note></note><note type="tag">bm:Taft1986Liturgy</note><citedRange unit="page">266</citedRange></bibl> are: </p>
            <p>
               <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT3575Mashaf">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</ref>: the Saʿātāt of <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4709Giyorgis">Giyorgis of Saglā</persName>,
               which replaced the <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2230Saatat">Saʿātāt za-gǝbṣ element TEI with id LIT2230Saatat</ref>:  and is presently in use in Ethiopia and Eritrea;</p>
            <p>
               <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT3576Saatat">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</ref>:  a Saʿātāt that includes the entire Psalter in the daily pensum;</p>
            <p>
               <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT3577GizeS">Gize ṣalot</ref>: a cursus of prayers which is not really a Saʿātāt, but a Gize ṣalot for hermits and recluses.</p>
           <p>
               <listBibl type="secondary">
                  <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/JA53S2XR"><seg type="encyclopediaArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:ZanettiFritsch2014Saatat"/><title level="a">Säʿatat: Mäṣḥafä säʿatat</title><title type="short">EAe</title><title level="m">Encyclopaedia Aethiopica</title><author><forename>Ugo</forename><surname>Zanetti</surname></author><author><forename>Emmanuel</forename><surname>Fritsch</surname></author><editor><forename>Alessandro</forename><surname>Bausi</surname></editor><editor><forename>Siegbert</forename><surname>Uhlig</surname></editor><pubPlace>Wiesbaden</pubPlace><publisher>Harrassowitz Verlag</publisher><date>2014</date><biblScope unit="volume">V</biblScope><biblScope unit="page">501a-503a</biblScope><note type="tags"><note type="tag">bm:ZanettiFritsch2014Saatat</note></note><note type="tag">bm:ZanettiFritsch2014Saatat</note></bibl>
               </listBibl>
            </p>
         </abstract>
